%N A297041 Number of pieces in the list d(m), d(m-1), ..., d(0) of base-13 digits of n; see Comments.
%C A297041 The definition of "piece" starts with the base-b digits d(m), d(m-1), ..., d(0) of n.  First, an *ascent* is a list (d(i), d(i-1), ..., d(i-h)) such that d(i) < d(i-1) < ... < d(i-h), where d(i+1) >= d(i) if i < m, and d(i-h-1) >= d(i-h) if i > h.  A *descent* is a list (d(i), d(i-1), ..., d(i-h)) such that d(i) > d(i-1) > ... > d(i-h), where d(i+1) <= d(i) if i < m, and d(i-h-1) <= d(i-h) if i > h.  A *flat* is a list (d(i), d(i-1), ..., d(i-h)), where h > 0, such that d(i) = d(i-1) = ... = d(i-h), where d(i+1) != d(i) if i < m, and d(i-h-1) != d(i-h) if i > h. A *piece* is an ascent, a descent, or a flat.  Example:  235621103 has five pieces:  (2,3,5,6), (6,2,1), (1,1), (1,0), and (0,3); that's 2 ascents, 2 descents, and 1 flat. For every b, the "piece sequence" includes every positive integer infinitely many times. See A297030 for a guide to related sequences.
%H A297041 Clark Kimberling, <a href="/A297041/b297041.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%e A297041 Base-13 digits for 1234567:  3, 4, 2, 12, 1, 9, so that a(124567) = 5.
%t A297041 a[n_, b_] := Length[Map[Length, Split[Sign[Differences[IntegerDigits[n, b]]]]]];
%t A297041 b = 13; Table[a[n, b], {n, 1, 1000}]
